<p class="breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a> &rsaquo; Spouse Filing</p>
<h1>Filing Bankruptcy Without Your Spouse (and What Happens to Community Property)</h1>
<p class="tagline">"Can my spouse file alone" has two different answers depending on your state. Here is the full picture - the 9 community-property states, the community-debt rule, and the deed-on-parents edge case.</p>
<a href="https://1328f.com/" class="cta">Free eligibility screener &rarr;</a>

<p>The single most common question in a joint-finances bankruptcy consult is some version of <em>"does my spouse have to file too?"</em> The answer is no - one spouse can file alone in every state. But the consequences of that choice depend entirely on whether you live in a <strong>community-property state</strong> or a <strong>common-law state</strong>, and that single fact changes what debts get discharged, what property the trustee can reach, and whether your non-filing spouse's financial life stays untouched.</p>

<h2>The Two Systems - Why State Law Matters</h2>

<div class="state-card">
<h3><span class="state-name">Common-law states (41 states + DC)</span></h3>
<p>Each spouse owns what is titled in their name. Debts contracted by one spouse are that spouse's debt unless jointly signed. When one spouse files, the trustee reaches that spouse's individually-owned property and discharges that spouse's individually-owed debts. The non-filing spouse's solo accounts, solo assets, and solo debts are unaffected.</p>
<p><strong>Practical read:</strong> individual filing is clean. The non-filing spouse is barely on the bankruptcy's radar except as a household-income participant for the means test.</p>
</div>

<div class="state-card">
<h3><span class="state-name">Community-property states (9 + opt-in AK)</span></h3>
<p>Most property acquired during the marriage is <em>community property</em> - owned 50/50 regardless of title. Most debts contracted during the marriage are <em>community debts</em> - both spouses are on the hook. When one spouse files, the community-property discharge under <strong>11 U.S.C. § 524(a)(3)</strong> extends to community debts, even though the non-filing spouse never signed the petition. In exchange, the trustee can reach community property - including assets technically titled in the non-filing spouse's name - to satisfy those debts.</p>
<p><strong>Practical read:</strong> individual filing in a community-property state is effectively a household-level event. The non-filing spouse benefits (community debts vanish) and is at risk (community assets enter the estate) in the same case.</p>
</div>

<h2>The 9 Community-Property States</h2>

<table>
<tr><th>State</th><th>Code citation</th><th>Peculiarity</th></tr>
<tr><td>Arizona</td><td>A.R.S. §§ 25-211 to 25-318</td><td>Income is community from the first day of marriage</td></tr>
<tr><td>California</td><td>Cal. Fam. Code §§ 760-1103</td><td>Broadest community-property regime; quasi-community property for out-of-state acquisitions</td></tr>
<tr><td>Idaho</td><td>Idaho Code §§ 32-903 to 32-920</td><td>Income from separate property is community unless expressly reserved</td></tr>
<tr><td>Louisiana</td><td>La. Civ. Code arts. 2334-2369</td><td>Civil law origin; default regime is community with option to contract out</td></tr>
<tr><td>Nevada</td><td>NRS §§ 123.010-123.270</td><td>Community property with right of survivorship allowed; key for estate planning</td></tr>
<tr><td>New Mexico</td><td>N.M. Stat. §§ 40-3-8 to 40-3-17</td><td>Personal injury recoveries are community property of the marriage</td></tr>
<tr><td>Texas</td><td>Tex. Fam. Code §§ 3.001-3.410</td><td>Liberal homestead exemption; income from separate property is community</td></tr>
<tr><td>Washington</td><td>RCW 26.16.010-26.16.150</td><td>Community income includes earnings from separate property</td></tr>
<tr><td>Wisconsin</td><td>Wis. Stat. §§ 766.001-766.97</td><td>Marital property act (functionally community property since 1986)</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Alaska is a 10th option, but opt-in only - couples must sign a community-property agreement to invoke it, and few do. The remaining 41 states plus DC are common-law.</p>

<h2>Community Property in Bankruptcy - What Changes</h2>

<h3>What becomes property of the estate</h3>
<p>When one spouse files in a community-property state, <strong>11 U.S.C. § 541(a)(2)</strong> pulls <em>all community property under the joint management of either spouse</em> into the bankruptcy estate. This is a significant expansion compared to a common-law filing, where only the filing spouse's individually-titled property enters the estate.</p>
<p>The practical result: in California or Texas, a savings account in the non-filing spouse's name alone may still be community property (deposited during marriage, from wages), and the trustee can reach it. In Ohio or New York (common-law states), the same account titled in the non-filing spouse's name is untouchable.</p>

<h3>What debts get discharged - the § 524(a)(3) community discharge</h3>
<p>Under <strong>11 U.S.C. § 524(a)(3)</strong>, the filing spouse's discharge operates as an injunction against collecting any community debt from community property - even debts the non-filing spouse signed for. This is the "phantom discharge" that protects non-filing spouses in community-property states.</p>
<p>Example: in Arizona, husband files Chapter 7 alone. A credit card in wife's name alone but opened during marriage is a community debt. Husband's discharge prevents the creditor from pursuing <em>any community property</em> for that debt - effectively discharging it as to the household. The creditor can still pursue the wife's <em>separate property</em> (inherited assets, pre-marriage savings), but in most households that pool is small or nonexistent.</p>

<h3>The non-filing spouse's credit</h3>
<p>A common worry, a simple answer: your individual bankruptcy filing does <strong>not</strong> appear on your spouse's credit report. It appears only on yours. However:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Jointly-held accounts</strong> (co-signed credit cards, joint auto loans, joint mortgages) show the bankruptcy notation on the non-filing spouse's credit report for that specific joint account.</li>
<li><strong>Separate accounts in your spouse's name only</strong> are untouched. Their credit score drops only to the extent joint accounts drop.</li>
<li><strong>Community-debt discharge</strong> means creditors cannot re-report the discharged debt as current - but they can and do continue reporting the debt as "included in bankruptcy" or "discharged" on your spouse's report if it was a joint account.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Joint vs Individual Filing - Choosing</h2>

<p>Joint filing (one petition, two filers) is available in every state under <strong>11 U.S.C. § 302</strong>. The decision between joint and individual filing turns on four variables:</p>

<table>
<tr><th>Factor</th><th>Joint filing</th><th>Individual filing</th></tr>
<tr><td>Attorney fees</td><td>One set</td><td>One set (one spouse)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Filing fee</td><td>$338 once</td><td>$338 once</td></tr>
<tr><td>Exemptions</td><td>Doubled in federal scheme + many states</td><td>Single</td></tr>
<tr><td>Debt coverage</td><td>Both spouses' debts</td><td>Only filing spouse (plus community in 9 states)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Asset exposure</td><td>Both spouses' separate + community</td><td>Filing spouse's separate + community</td></tr>
<tr><td>Credit impact</td><td>Both spouses' reports</td><td>Filing spouse's report; joint accounts show on both</td></tr>
<tr><td>Timing</td><td>Must align (1328(f) bar, means test)</td><td>Flexible by spouse</td></tr>
</table>

<p>The standard recommendation: <strong>file jointly</strong> unless a specific factor pushes toward individual. Those specific factors:</p>

<div class="state-card">
<h3>When individual filing makes sense</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Only one spouse has dischargeable debt.</strong> If the debt is all in one spouse's name (premarital, or solely-signed), there is nothing for the other to discharge.</li>
<li><strong>One spouse is inside the 1328(f) bar.</strong> If one spouse received a Chapter 7 discharge less than 8 years ago, they cannot file another Chapter 7 now. The other spouse can file individually.</li>
<li><strong>One spouse has significant non-exempt assets.</strong> In a community-property state this benefit is limited (trustee reaches community property anyway), but in a common-law state, keeping the high-asset spouse out of the filing preserves their property.</li>
<li><strong>One spouse's income disqualifies joint under the means test but individual would qualify.</strong> Rare, because household income is aggregated for the means test regardless of who files - but possible in specific marital-adjustment scenarios.</li>
<li><strong>One spouse is an immigration-status concern.</strong> Bankruptcy filing is public record; some non-citizens prefer not to appear on PACER.</li>
</ul>
</div>

<h2>Scenarios - How This Plays Out</h2>

<div class="state-card">
<h3>Scenario 1 - California couple, $90k joint credit-card debt, one W-2 earner</h3>
<p>California is community property. Either filing individually or jointly produces the same economic result for the household: the community-debt discharge under § 524(a)(3) wipes the cards regardless. Joint is still cheaper (one attorney retainer, doubled California homestead exemption) and gives the non-filing spouse a clean discharge on their individual report. Joint wins.</p>
</div>

<div class="state-card">
<h3>Scenario 2 - Ohio couple, $60k debt in husband's name only (premarital)</h3>
<p>Ohio is common-law. The wife has no liability on husband's premarital debt. Individual filing by husband is clean - wife's credit, income, and property are untouched except as a household-income input for the means test. Individual wins.</p>
</div>

<div class="state-card">
<h3>Scenario 3 - Texas couple, husband owns inherited family business ($400k equity), wife has $75k CC debt in her name</h3>
<p>Texas is community property. If wife files individually, the trustee can reach community assets including community earnings, but the business is husband's separate property (inherited, not community). However, any distributions from the business during the marriage that were deposited into joint accounts are community. Individual filing by wife protects the business itself; joint filing does not. Individual wins <em>if</em> the business structure is documented as separate property.</p>
</div>

<div class="state-card">
<h3>Scenario 4 - Washington couple, both have debt, wife discharged in Chapter 7 four years ago</h3>
<p>Washington is community property. Wife is inside the 8-year 1328(f) bar and cannot re-file Chapter 7. Husband can file Chapter 7 individually now; § 524(a)(3) extends the community-debt discharge to wife's share of community debts automatically. Four years from now, wife can file her own Chapter 7 if any solely-held debt remains. Staggered individual filings win.</p>
</div>

<h2>The Deed-on-Parents Edge Case</h2>

<div class="warning">
<p><strong>Being on a deed to a parent's house is a property interest under the Bankruptcy Code.</strong> It is the single most common "gotcha" for pro-se filers and thinly-supervised cases. Under <strong>11 U.S.C. § 541(a)(1)</strong>, all "legal or equitable interests of the debtor in property" enter the estate as of the filing date. A fractional deed interest - even one added "just for convenience" or for estate-planning - qualifies.</p>
</div>

<p>What typically happens: a parent ages, the adult child is added to the deed so they can handle the property after death without probate, and years later the child files bankruptcy without realizing they need to disclose (and protect) their deed interest. The trustee sees the property on the county assessor's records, asks about it at the 341 meeting, and now there is an asset issue.</p>

<h3>How it gets resolved</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Disclose.</strong> Always list the interest on Schedule A/B. Failure to disclose is grounds for denial of discharge under <strong>11 U.S.C. § 727(a)(4)</strong> and can be charged as bankruptcy fraud under 18 U.S.C. § 152.</li>
<li><strong>Value it.</strong> The estate's interest is your fractional share of the current market value, minus any mortgage balance, pro-rated. A one-third interest in a $300,000 unencumbered house is a $100,000 asset (subject to any applicable homestead).</li>
<li><strong>Apply exemptions if possible.</strong> If you live in the house, your state's homestead exemption applies to your share. If you do not live in the house - which is the usual situation - the homestead usually does not protect non-occupant interests. Some states (e.g., Texas, Florida) have broader homestead rules, but the "I don't live there" fact pattern breaks most of them.</li>
<li><strong>Trustee's options.</strong> The trustee may abandon the interest under <strong>§ 554(a)</strong> if administering it would not benefit creditors (small interests, complicated partition). Or the trustee may sell the estate's interest to a third party (rare) or negotiate a buyout with the parent. A parent-funded buyout of the child's deed interest is the most common resolution.</li>
</ol>

<div class="yellow">
<p><strong>Removing yourself from the deed before filing does not solve the problem - it creates a different one.</strong> A transfer within two years of filing is subject to <strong>§ 548</strong> fraudulent-transfer clawback; within four years or more under state fraudulent-transfer law (most states' Uniform Voidable Transactions Act). You must disclose any transfer in the last 4 years under Question 18 of the Statement of Financial Affairs. "I just took my name off the deed last month" is a trustee magnet.</p>
</div>

<p>The only clean paths through a deed-on-parents situation are (a) transfer off the deed and wait 4+ years before filing, or (b) disclose it, value it, and resolve it during the case. There is no shortcut. This is not a DIY scenario.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked</h2>

<div class="faq">
<h3>Does my spouse have to go to the 341 meeting if I file alone?</h3>
<p>No. Only the filing spouse attends. Some trustees ask the non-filing spouse to appear voluntarily if the case involves community property - it is polite to have them on standby by phone - but there is no legal requirement.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq">
<h3>Does my spouse's income count in the means test?</h3>
<p>Yes, under <strong>11 U.S.C. § 707(b)(2)</strong>. Household income - both spouses - is counted for the median-income comparison even if only one spouse files. You can deduct a "marital adjustment" for the non-filing spouse's expenses that do not benefit the household (their student loans, their car payment, their support of a child from a prior relationship).</p>
</div>

<div class="faq">
<h3>Can I hide my spouse's income in the means test?</h3>
<p>No. Line 3 of Form 122A-1 asks for "spouse's income" and failing to report it is perjury on a sworn document. Trustees cross-check against tax returns.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq">
<h3>What about registered domestic partners or civil unions?</h3>
<p>Community-property treatment for registered domestic partners varies - California treats them as married for state-law property purposes; most other states do not. Federal bankruptcy law references "spouse" (§ 302, § 522(m), § 524(a)(3)); unmarried partners cannot file a joint petition. Consult a local attorney for civil-union specifics in your state.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq">
<h3>What if we filed for divorce but it's not final?</h3>
<p>Timing gets complex. Property acquired during the marriage is still community property in community-property states until the divorce is final. Bankruptcy courts often defer to pending divorce proceedings on property division. File jointly before filing for divorce, or wait until the divorce decree is final before filing bankruptcy - filing during a pending divorce creates cross-court complications that almost always require counsel on both cases.</p>
</div>

